Instance families, naming, and the T-series.

Instance types group into families by workload shape. You pick the family first, then the size. General Purpose, like t-three and m-seven-g, balances C-P-U, memory, and network, for web servers and small databases. Compute Optimised, like c-seven-g, gives the most C-P-U per dollar, for batch jobs, gaming, and H-P-C. Memory Optimised, like r-seven-g and x-two-i-d-n, packs R-A-M per core, for in-memory databases. Storage Optimised, like i-four-i, delivers local N-V-M-e throughput, for NoSQL and warehouses. And Accelerated Computing, like p-four and inf-two, adds G-P-Us and custom chips for machine learning.

The name encodes everything. Take m-seven-g-dot-x-large. The m is the family. The seven is the generation. The g is the processor, in this case Graviton, which is AWS's own A-R-M chip; you'll also see i for Intel and a for A-M-D, plus n for network-optimised and d for local N-V-M-e. And x-large is the size. Sizes roughly double the v-C-P-U and R-A-M at each step. Graviton is usually about twenty percent cheaper and forty percent better performance-per-dollar than x-eighty-six, so it's the default first choice when your workload runs on A-R-M.

The T-series, t-three and t-four-g, is a special case: it's burstable. It runs at a baseline C-P-U percentage, earns credits when it's below baseline, and spends them to burst above it. Unlimited mode, which is the default, keeps bursting at extra cost; Standard mode caps at baseline. It's perfect for spiky, mostly-idle workloads like low-traffic sites and dev boxes, but it's wrong for sustained C-P-U, where you'll either throttle or pay the overage.
